hands_on_practices.solution:
We seek $\alpha$ such that the destruction timescale $T_{\rm dest}(m)$ is independent of $m$.  

1. Radius–mass relation for uniform density $\rho$:
$$R(m)=\Bigl(\frac{3m}{4\pi\rho}\Bigr)^{1/3}\;\propto\;m^{1/3}.$$

2. Fragmentation threshold: equate projectile KE to binding energy,
$$\tfrac12\,m_{\rm crit}\,v_0^2\Bigl(\frac{m}{m_0}\Bigr)^{2\zeta}
=Q_0\,m\Bigl(\frac{m}{m_0}\Bigr)^{\delta},$$
so
$$m_{\rm crit}
=2\,Q_0\,v_0^{-2}\,m_0^{2\zeta-\delta}\;m^{\,1+\delta-2\zeta}
\;\propto\;m^{\,1+\delta-2\zeta}.$$

3. Collision kernel for $m\gg m_{\rm crit}$:
$$K(m,m_{\rm crit})
\approx\pi R^2\,v_{\rm rel}(m)\;\propto\;
m^{2/3}\,m^{\zeta}=m^{\,2/3+\zeta}.$$

4. Destruction rate dominated by projectiles of mass $m_{\rm crit}$:
$$T_{\rm dest}^{-1}(m)\propto
K(m,m_{\rm crit})\;n(m_{\rm crit})\;m_{\rm crit}
\propto m^{2/3+\zeta}\;
\bigl(m^{1+\delta-2\zeta}\bigr)^{-\alpha}\;
m^{1+\delta-2\zeta}.$$

5. Require exponent of $m$ to vanish:
$$2/3+\zeta+(1+\delta-2\zeta)-\alpha(1+\delta-2\zeta)=0
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\alpha=\frac{\tfrac{5}{3}+\delta-\zeta}{1+\delta-2\zeta}.$$
